                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d852">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812,00/14674.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">British Minister to Mexico</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">British Ambassador at Washington</gloss>.</hi>
                    <note n="19" xml:id="d852fn19">Copy left at the Department of State, March 18,
                        1915.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mexico City</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-03-17">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 17, 1915</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Minister for Foreign Affairs states that he is prepared to consider
                    neutralization of Mexican railways. * * * None of us here have the vaguest idea
                    of the state of affairs in the northern part of the Republic. I cannot but
                    consider present improvement in situation as trifling and temporary, the real
                    gravity of conditions has in no way diminished.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hohler.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
